lcaEntry.name: AL 5052 Honeycomb with CFRP facing [mass] | production
lcaEntry.displayName: AL 5052 Honeycomb with CFRP facing [mass] , RER
lcaEntry.description: Functional Unit: production 1 kg of aluminium honeycomb sandwich panel with CFRP facing skins (0.12369 m2 per 1 kg).Included Processes: Includes material inputs including: aluminium honeycomb, CFRP and adhesive. General Comment: An average thickness from 3 to 40 mm is assumed for aluminium honeycomb core. This range is considered adequate to prevent the panel from buckling and the core from prematurely failing in shear under end compression loads. Alloys density is used to determine input material quantification. An average thickness from 0,145 mm and 3 mm is assumed for CFRP facings. The autoclave production process is considered as the most appropriate process to produce high quality CFRP elements. Adhesive thicknesses from 0,3 mm to 1 mm is assumed. Inventory quantification equations are available in the report "Pettersen JB, Bergsdal H, Silva EJ, Bjørnbet MM, Estrela MA, Chaves PA, Skaar C, Aschehoug S (2015): D3.3 Environmental impact of space materials and processes - final iteration. lcaEntry.name: Cylindrical Tank, Titanium primary, average, [mass] | production
lcaEntry.displayName: Cylindrical Tank, Titanium primary, average, [mass] , RER
lcaEntry.description: Functional Unit: production of a cylindrical Titanium alloy tank with a volume of 1 m3.Included Processes: Includes tank and PMD material, machining processes, heat treatment, welding, cleaning and NDI inspections. Material removed from forging material is accounted by machining processes. Infrastructure covered by manufacturing processes.General Comment: The tank production process starts with forging of alloy tank material. Each forging is rough machined, solution heat treated and quenched, partial aged, skim machined and finish machined. After the completion of the tank shell, a PMD shaft are welded to the propellant hemisphere to form the PMD base, and the inlet and outlet tubes are welded to the hemispheres. The assembled PMD is then installed onto the PMD shaft to complete the expulsion assembly. Depending on the tank geometry, one or two girth welds are required to assemble the tank. For cylindrical tanks two girth welds are required. In this case, the first weld joins the pressurant hemisphere and the centre section, and the second joins the hemisphere/centre ring assembly to the expulsion assembly to complete the tank closure. After closure the tank assembly is stress relieved and aged, usually in a vacuum furnace. A final machine operation is also performed prior to acceptance testing. Acceptance test includes: Volumetric Capacity examination, Proof Pressure Inspection, Pressure Cycle Inspection, Negative Pressure Inspection, Vibration Test, Total Design Loads Inspection, Expulsion Efficiency Inspection  External Leak Inspection, Dye Penetrant Inspection, X-Ray/Radiographic Inspection, Ultrasonic Inspection and Automated Eddy Current inspection.Inventory quantification equations are available in the report "Pettersen JB, Bergsdal H, Silva EJ, Bjørnbet MM, Estrela MA, Chaves PA, Skaar C, Aschehoug S (2015): D3.3 Environmental impact of space materials and processes - final iteration. Asplan Viak, ISQ, Sintef Raufoss Manufacturing, under commission to European Space Agency. ESA contract 4000111095."Project: Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) of Manufacturing Process and Space Materials. ESA Contract No.4000111095/14/NL/GLC

lcaEntry.name: Carbon Fiber, high strength | production
lcaEntry.description: Functional Unit: production of 1 kg of carbon fibre.Included Processes: Includes direct electricity consumption as well as heat production, water, precursor and input materials consumption. Air and water emissions are also included.Infrastructure: infrastructure is not included.General Comment: The precursor polyacrylonitrile (PAN) is first spun into filament yarns, using chemical and mechanical processes to initially align the polymer atoms in a way to enhance the final physical properties of the completed carbon fibre. After drawing or spinning, the polymer filament yarns are then heated to drive off non-carbon atoms (carbonization), producing the final carbon fibre. The carbon fibres filament yarns are further treated to improve handling qualities, and then wound on to bobbins.Main source: E. Griffing, M. Overcash (2010). Carbon fiber 50 wpct epoxy placeholder. Chemical Life Cycle Database. Environmental Clarity.Project: Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) of Manufacturing Process and Space Materials. ESA Contract No.4000111095/14/NL/GLC

lcaEntry.description: Functional Unit: production of a cylindrical Titanium alloy tank with a volume of 1 m3.Included Processes: Includes tank and PMD material, machining processes, heat treatment, welding, cleaning and NDI inspections. Material removed from forging material is accounted by machining processes. Infrastructure covered by manufacturing processes.General Comment: The tank production process starts with forging of alloy tank material. Each forging is rough machined, solution heat treated and quenched, partial aged, skim machined and finish machined. After the completion of the tank shell, a PMD shaft are welded to the propellant hemisphere to form the PMD base, and the inlet and outlet tubes are welded to the hemispheres. The assembled PMD is then installed onto the PMD shaft to complete the expulsion assembly. Depending on the tank geometry, one or two girth welds are required to assemble the tank. For cylindrical tanks two girth welds are required. In this case, the first weld joins the pressurant hemisphere and the centre section, and the second joins the hemisphere/centre ring assembly to the expulsion assembly to complete the tank closure. After closure the tank assembly is stress relieved and aged, usually in a vacuum furnace. A final machine operation is also performed prior to acceptance testing. Acceptance test includes: Volumetric Capacity examination, Proof Pressure Inspection, Pressure Cycle Inspection, Negative Pressure Inspection, Vibration Test, Total Design Loads Inspection, Expulsion Efficiency Inspection  External Leak Inspection, Dye Penetrant Inspection, X-Ray/Radiographic Inspection, Ultrasonic Inspection and Automated Eddy Current inspection.Inventory quantification equations are available in the report "Pettersen JB, Bergsdal H, Silva EJ, Bjørnbet MM, Estrela MA, Chaves PA, Skaar C, Aschehoug S (2015): D3.3 Environmental impact of space materials and processes - final iteration. The carbon fibres filament yarns are further treated to improve handling qualities, and then wound on to bobbins.Main source: E. Griffing, M. Overcash (2010). Carbon fiber 50 wpct epoxy placeholder. lcaEntry.name: Cylindrical Tank, Titanium primary, average, [mass] | production
lcaEntry.displayName: Cylindrical Tank, Titanium primary, average, [mass] , RER
lcaEntry.description: Functional Unit: production of a cylindrical Titanium alloy tank with a volume of 1 m3.Included Processes: Includes tank and PMD material, machining processes, heat treatment, welding, cleaning and NDI inspections. Material removed from forging material is accounted by machining processes. Infrastructure covered by manufacturing processes.General Comment: The tank production process starts with forging of alloy tank material. Each forging is rough machined, solution heat treated and quenched, partial aged, skim machined and finish machined. After the completion of the tank shell, a PMD shaft are welded to the propellant hemisphere to form the PMD base, and the inlet and outlet tubes are welded to the hemispheres. The assembled PMD is then installed onto the PMD shaft to complete the expulsion assembly. Depending on the tank geometry, one or two girth welds are required to assemble the tank. For cylindrical tanks two girth welds are required. In this case, the first weld joins the pressurant hemisphere and the centre section, and the second joins the hemisphere/centre ring assembly to the expulsion assembly to complete the tank closure. After closure the tank assembly is stress relieved and aged, usually in a vacuum furnace. A final machine operation is also performed prior to acceptance testing. Acceptance test includes: Volumetric Capacity examination, Proof Pressure Inspection, Pressure Cycle Inspection, Negative Pressure Inspection, Vibration Test, Total Design Loads Inspection, Expulsion Efficiency Inspection  External Leak Inspection, Dye Penetrant Inspection, X-Ray/Radiographic Inspection, Ultrasonic Inspection and Automated Eddy Current inspection.Inventory quantification equations are available in the report "Pettersen JB, Bergsdal H, Silva EJ, Bjørnbet MM, Estrela MA, Chaves PA, Skaar C, Aschehoug S (2015): D3.3 Environmental impact of space materials and processes - final iteration. Asplan Viak, ISQ, Sintef Raufoss Manufacturing, under commission to European Space Agency. ESA contract 4000111095."Project: Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) of Manufacturing Process and Space Materials. ESA Contract No.4000111095/14/NL/GLC
